def L(lv,t,c,code='',tip=''):return(lv,t,c,code,tip)
REACT=[
L(1,'What is React?','React is a JavaScript library for building user interfaces. Created by Facebook (Meta), it breaks pages into small, reusable pieces called components. Each component is a function that returns JSX — HTML-like syntax that React converts to real DOM elements.','import React from "react";\n\nfunction App() {\n  return <h1>Hello, React!</h1>;\n}\n\nexport default App;','React is a library, not a framework. It focuses only on the UI layer. You add routing, state management, and other features with separate packages.'),
L(1,'JSX — JavaScript XML','JSX lets you write HTML-like code inside JavaScript. Use curly braces {} to embed JavaScript expressions (variables, math, function calls). JSX must return a single parent element — use <div> or empty fragments <></> to wrap multiple elements.','function Greeting() {\n  const name = "Alice";\n  return (\n    <>\n      <h1>Hello, {name}!</h1>\n      <p>{2 + 2} is four</p>\n      <p>Today: {new Date().toLocaleDateString()}</p>\n    </>\n  );\n}','In JSX, use className instead of class (since class is a reserved word in JavaScript), and htmlFor instead of for on label elements.'),
L(2,'Creating Components','Components are functions that return JSX. They are the building blocks of React apps. Component names MUST start with a capital letter — React treats lowercase names as regular HTML tags.','function Header() {\n  return <header><h1>My App</h1></header>;\n}\nfunction Footer() {\n  return <footer><p>© 2024</p></footer>;\n}\nfunction App() {\n  return (\n    <>\n      <Header />\n      <main>Content</main>\n      <Footer />\n    </>\n  );\n}','Component names must start with a capital letter: <Header /> is a component, <header> is an HTML tag. This distinction matters to React.'),
L(2,'Component Files and Exports','Each component typically lives in its own file. Use export default to make a component available to other files, and import to bring it in. Keep components small and focused on one job.','// Button.jsx\nexport default function Button({ label }) {\n  return <button>{label}</button>;\n}\n\n// App.jsx\nimport Button from "./Button";\nfunction App() {\n  return <Button label="Click me" />;\n}','Export components with export default (one per file) or named export (multiple per file). The import syntax differs for each.'),
L(3,'Props — Passing Data','Props (properties) pass data from parent to child components. They are read-only — a child component CANNOT modify its own props. Props flow one-way: parent → child. Use destructuring in function parameters to access them cleanly.','function UserCard({ name, age, role }) {\n  return (\n    <div className="card">\n      <h2>{name}</h2>\n      <p>Age: {age}</p>\n      <span>{role}</span>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n// Usage:\n<UserCard name="Alice" age={25} role="Admin" />','String props use quotes: name="Alice". Numbers, booleans, and expressions use curly braces: age={25}, active={true}.'),
L(3,'The children Prop','The special children prop contains everything placed between a component\'s opening and closing tags. This makes wrapper components flexible — they display whatever content is passed inside them.','function Card({ title, children }) {\n  return (\n    <div className="card">\n      <h3>{title}</h3>\n      <div>{children}</div>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n// Usage:\n<Card title="Settings">\n  <p>Any content here!</p>\n  <button>Save</button>\n</Card>','The children prop is automatically available — you do not need to pass it explicitly. Just place content between the opening and closing tags.'),
L(4,'State with useState','State is data that changes over time. When state updates, React automatically re-renders the component to display the new values. useState returns an array with two items: the current value and a setter function.','import { useState } from "react";\n\nfunction Counter() {\n  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <p>Count: {count}</p>\n      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>\n        Add\n      </button>\n    </div>\n  );\n}','Never modify state directly (count++ is WRONG). Always use the setter function (setCount) — it tells React to re-render with the new value.'),
L(4,'Updating State Safely','When the new state depends on the previous state, use the function form of the setter: setCount(prev => prev + 1). This ensures you always work with the latest value, avoiding bugs from stale state.','// May miss updates under rapid clicks:\nsetCount(count + 1);\n\n// Safe — always uses latest value:\nsetCount(prev => prev + 1);\n\n// Object state — always spread first:\nconst [user, setUser] = useState({ name: "", age: 0 });\nsetUser(prev => ({ ...prev, name: "Alice" }));','When updating object or array state, always create a new copy with spread (...prev). Mutating the existing object will NOT trigger a re-render.'),
L(5,'Handling Events','React events use camelCase names: onClick, onChange, onSubmit, onKeyDown. Pass a function reference as the handler — do NOT call it directly. The event object (e) contains information about the interaction.','function Form() {\n  const handleClick = () => {\n    alert("Clicked!");\n  };\n  const handleInput = (e) => {\n    console.log(e.target.value);\n  };\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <button onClick={handleClick}>Click</button>\n      <input onChange={handleInput} />\n    </div>\n  );\n}','onClick={handleClick} passes a function reference (correct). onClick={handleClick()} CALLS the function immediately during render (wrong).'),
L(5,'Preventing Default Behavior','Use e.preventDefault() inside event handlers to stop default browser behavior like form submission (page reload) or link navigation. This is essential for single-page applications.','function SearchForm({ onSearch }) {\n  const [query, setQuery] = useState("");\n  const handleSubmit = (e) => {\n    e.preventDefault();\n    onSearch(query);\n  };\n  return (\n    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>\n      <input\n        value={query}\n        onChange={e => setQuery(e.target.value)}\n      />\n      <button type="submit">Search</button>\n    </form>\n  );\n}','Always call e.preventDefault() on form submit in React. Without it, the page reloads and all component state is lost.'),
L(6,'Conditional Rendering','Show different content based on conditions using ternary operators (? :) or the && shorthand. The ternary renders one of two options, while && renders something only when the condition is true.','function Status({ isOnline }) {\n  return (\n    <div>\n      {isOnline ? (\n        <span className="green">Online</span>\n      ) : (\n        <span className="gray">Offline</span>\n      )}\n      {isOnline && <p>Available to chat</p>}\n    </div>\n  );\n}','The && shorthand: {condition && <Element />} renders <Element /> only when condition is truthy. If condition is false, nothing is rendered.'),
L(6,'Rendering Nothing and Early Returns','Return null from a component to render nothing. Use early returns at the top of a component to handle loading states, missing data, or permission checks before rendering the main content.','function AdminPanel({ user }) {\n  if (!user || !user.isAdmin) {\n    return null;\n  }\n  return <div>Admin controls here</div>;\n}\n\nfunction App() {\n  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);\n  if (loading) return <Spinner />;\n  return <Dashboard />;\n}','Early returns keep code clean — check edge cases at the top of the component, then render the main content without nested conditionals.'),
L(7,'Rendering Lists with map()','Use .map() to transform an array of data into an array of JSX elements. Every item in a list MUST have a unique key prop — React uses keys to efficiently track which items changed, were added, or removed.','function TodoList({ todos }) {\n  return (\n    <ul>\n      {todos.map(todo => (\n        <li key={todo.id}>\n          {todo.text}\n        </li>\n      ))}\n    </ul>\n  );\n}','Use a unique ID (like database ID) as the key — NOT the array index. Array indexes cause bugs when items are reordered or deleted.'),
L(7,'Filtering and Chaining','Combine .filter() and .map() to show only items matching a condition. Chain array methods for powerful data transformations: .filter().sort().map() is a common React pattern.','function ActiveUsers({ users }) {\n  return (\n    <ul>\n      {users\n        .filter(u => u.isActive)\n        .sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name))\n        .map(u => (\n          <li key={u.id}>{u.name}</li>\n        ))}\n    </ul>\n  );\n}','Chain .filter().map() to first remove unwanted items, then transform the remaining ones into JSX elements.'),
L(8,'useEffect — Side Effects','useEffect runs code AFTER the component renders. Use it for side effects: fetching data, setting up timers, updating document title, or subscribing to events. Return a cleanup function to prevent memory leaks.','import { useState, useEffect } from "react";\n\nfunction Timer() {\n  const [seconds, setSeconds] = useState(0);\n  \n  useEffect(() => {\n    const id = setInterval(() => {\n      setSeconds(s => s + 1);\n    }, 1000);\n    return () => clearInterval(id);\n  }, []);\n  \n  return <p>{seconds}s</p>;\n}','The empty array [] means run once on mount. No array means run after EVERY render. [value] means run when value changes.'),
L(8,'Effect Dependencies','The dependency array controls WHEN the effect re-runs. Include every variable from outside the effect that it reads. Missing dependencies cause stale data bugs; extra dependencies cause unnecessary re-runs.','useEffect(() => {\n  // Runs when userId changes\n  fetchUser(userId).then(setUser);\n}, [userId]);\n\nuseEffect(() => {\n  // Runs once on mount only\n  loadSettings();\n}, []);\n\nuseEffect(() => {\n  // Runs after every render\n  document.title = `Count: ${count}`;\n});','The cleanup function (return () => {...}) runs before the next effect and on unmount. Always clean up timers, subscriptions, and event listeners.'),
L(9,'Controlled Forms','In controlled forms, React state is the single source of truth. Every input displays the value from state, and every change updates state via onChange. This gives you full control over form data.','function LoginForm() {\n  const [email, setEmail] = useState("");\n  const [pass, setPass] = useState("");\n  \n  const handleSubmit = (e) => {\n    e.preventDefault();\n    login(email, pass);\n  };\n  \n  return (\n    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>\n      <input\n        value={email}\n        onChange={e => setEmail(e.target.value)}\n      />\n      <input\n        type="password"\n        value={pass}\n        onChange={e => setPass(e.target.value)}\n      />\n    </form>\n  );\n}','A controlled input requires both value={state} and onChange={handler}. If you set value without onChange, the input becomes read-only.'),
L(9,'Form Validation','Validate inputs and show error messages conditionally. Validate on change for instant feedback, or on blur (when the user leaves the field) for a less intrusive experience.','const [email, setEmail] = useState("");\nconst [error, setError] = useState("");\n\nconst validate = (value) => {\n  if (!value.includes("@")) {\n    setError("Invalid email");\n  } else {\n    setError("");\n  }\n};\n\n<input\n  value={email}\n  onChange={e => {\n    setEmail(e.target.value);\n    validate(e.target.value);\n  }}\n/>\n{error && <p className="error">{error}</p>}','Validate on blur (onBlur event) for better UX — users don\'t want error messages while still typing. Validate on submit for final checks.'),
L(10,'Context API','Context passes data through the component tree without manually threading props through every level (called "prop drilling"). Use createContext, Provider (to supply data), and useContext (to consume it).','const ThemeContext = React.createContext("light");\n\nfunction App() {\n  return (\n    <ThemeContext.Provider value="dark">\n      <Page />\n    </ThemeContext.Provider>\n  );\n}\n\nfunction Button() {\n  const theme = useContext(ThemeContext);\n  return <button className={theme}>Click</button>;\n}','Context is ideal for global data: theme, language/locale, authentication state. Avoid using it for frequently changing data — it re-renders every consumer.'),
L(10,'Custom Context Pattern','Create a Provider component and a custom hook to make context usage clean across your app. This pattern encapsulates the context logic and provides a simple API for consumers.','// AuthContext.jsx\nconst AuthContext = createContext(null);\n\nexport function AuthProvider({ children }) {\n  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);\n  return (\n    <AuthContext.Provider value={{ user, setUser }}>\n      {children}\n    </AuthContext.Provider>\n  );\n}\n\nexport function useAuth() {\n  return useContext(AuthContext);\n}','The custom hook pattern (useAuth, useTheme, etc.) is the standard approach in production React apps for providing global state.'),
L(11,'Custom Hooks','Custom hooks extract reusable stateful logic from components. They are regular functions that start with "use" and can call other hooks (useState, useEffect, etc.). They follow the same rules as built-in hooks.','function useLocalStorage(key, initial) {\n  const [value, setValue] = useState(() => {\n    const stored = localStorage.getItem(key);\n    return stored ? JSON.parse(stored) : initial;\n  });\n  \n  useEffect(() => {\n    localStorage.setItem(key, JSON.stringify(value));\n  }, [key, value]);\n  \n  return [value, setValue];\n}\n// Usage:\nconst [theme, setTheme] = useLocalStorage("theme", "dark");','Custom hooks MUST start with "use" — this is how React knows to apply the rules of hooks (no conditionals, no loops).'),
L(11,'Common Custom Hook Patterns','Popular patterns: useToggle (boolean state), useFetch (data loading), useDebounce (delayed execution), useWindowSize (viewport tracking). Extract logic whenever you repeat the same useState + useEffect pattern.','function useToggle(initial = false) {\n  const [value, setValue] = useState(initial);\n  const toggle = () => setValue(v => !v);\n  return [value, toggle];\n}\n\n// Usage:\nconst [isOpen, toggleOpen] = useToggle();\n\n<button onClick={toggleOpen}>\n  {isOpen ? "Close" : "Open"}\n</button>','If you find yourself writing the same useState + useEffect combination in multiple components, that\'s a sign to extract it into a custom hook.'),
L(12,'useRef — Persistent Values','useRef stores a mutable value that persists between renders WITHOUT causing re-renders when it changes. It can also hold direct references to DOM elements for imperative operations like focusing inputs.','function TextInput() {\n  const inputRef = useRef(null);\n  \n  const focusInput = () => {\n    inputRef.current.focus();\n  };\n  \n  return (\n    <div>\n      <input ref={inputRef} />\n      <button onClick={focusInput}>\n        Focus\n      </button>\n    </div>\n  );\n}','useState triggers re-renders, useRef does not. Use useRef for timer IDs, previous values, DOM element access, and any mutable value that should not affect rendering.'),
L(12,'Direct DOM Access','Use refs to perform DOM operations that React cannot handle declaratively: measuring element dimensions, scrolling programmatically, integrating with third-party DOM libraries, or managing focus.','function ScrollToTop() {\n  const topRef = useRef(null);\n  \n  const scrollUp = () => {\n    topRef.current.scrollIntoView({\n      behavior: "smooth"\n    });\n  };\n  \n  return (\n    <div>\n      <div ref={topRef} />\n      {/* page content */}\n      <button onClick={scrollUp}>Top</button>\n    </div>\n  );\n}','Minimize direct DOM manipulation in React. Use refs only for operations React cannot handle declaratively (focus, scroll, measure).'),
L(13,'React.memo for Performance','React.memo wraps a component to prevent re-rendering when its props have not changed. This is a performance optimization for expensive components that render frequently with the same data.','const ExpensiveList = React.memo(function List({ items }) {\n  console.log("Rendering list...");\n  return (\n    <ul>\n      {items.map(item => (\n        <li key={item.id}>{item.name}</li>\n      ))}\n    </ul>\n  );\n});','Only use React.memo when you have a measured performance problem. Premature optimization adds code complexity for no real benefit.'),
L(13,'useMemo and useCallback','useMemo caches a computed value so it is not recalculated every render. useCallback caches a function reference so it is not recreated every render. Both take a dependency array — the cached value updates only when dependencies change.','const sortedItems = useMemo(() => {\n  return items.sort((a, b) =>\n    a.name.localeCompare(b.name));\n}, [items]);\n\nconst handleClick = useCallback((id) => {\n  setSelected(id);\n}, []);','useMemo is for expensive calculations. useCallback is for function references passed to memo-wrapped children. Don\'t use either without measuring first.'),
L(14,'Error Boundaries','Error boundaries catch JavaScript errors anywhere in their child component tree and display a fallback UI instead of crashing the entire application. They must be class components (not hooks-based).','class ErrorBoundary extends React.Component {\n  state = { hasError: false };\n  \n  static getDerivedStateFromError() {\n    return { hasError: true };\n  }\n  \n  render() {\n    if (this.state.hasError) {\n      return <h2>Something went wrong.</h2>;\n    }\n    return this.props.children;\n  }\n}\n// Usage:\n<ErrorBoundary>\n  <MyComponent />\n</ErrorBoundary>','Error boundaries catch render-time errors only. They do NOT catch errors in event handlers, async code (setTimeout, fetch), or the boundary component itself.'),
L(14,'Handling Async Errors','For errors in async operations (data fetching, API calls), use try/catch with error state. Display user-friendly error messages and provide a way to retry the failed operation.','function UserProfile({ userId }) {\n  const [error, setError] = useState(null);\n  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);\n  \n  useEffect(() => {\n    fetchUser(userId)\n      .then(setUser)\n      .catch(err => setError(err.message));\n  }, [userId]);\n  \n  if (error) return <p>Error: {error}</p>;\n  if (!user) return <p>Loading...</p>;\n  return <h1>{user.name}</h1>;\n}','Always show meaningful error messages. The loading → error → success pattern (with state for each) is the standard approach for data fetching in React.'),
L(15,'React Design Patterns','Production React apps use established patterns: compound components (related components that work together), render props (passing JSX via function), and higher-order components (functions that enhance components).','// Compound components\n<Tabs>\n  <Tabs.Tab label="Profile">\n    <ProfileContent />\n  </Tabs.Tab>\n  <Tabs.Tab label="Settings">\n    <SettingsContent />\n  </Tabs.Tab>\n</Tabs>','Custom hooks have replaced most use cases for render props and HOCs. Choose the simplest pattern that solves your problem.'),
L(15,'State Management Strategies','Choose the right state tool based on complexity: useState for local state, useReducer for complex state logic, Context for shared app state, and external libraries (Redux, Zustand) for very large applications.','// Local state\nconst [count, setCount] = useState(0);\n\n// Shared state via Context\nconst { user } = useAuth();\n\n// Complex state with useReducer\nconst [state, dispatch] = useReducer(\n  reducer,\n  initialState\n);','useReducer is built into React and handles complex state with actions and a reducer function — similar to Redux but without extra dependencies.'),
]
